Headlines.Headline: U.S. Hog Futures Slip As Pork Prices Decline; Demand Caution

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Kelsey Gee CHICAGO--U.S. hog futures are tumbling in electronic trade as wholesale pork values have slipped modestly, fueling concerns that demand for record-priced loins, bellies, and other items may start to weaken in the weeks ahead. A surge in wholesale pork prices to the highest levels in history has added to worries that restaurants and grocery stores may reduce purchases if they are unable to pass on costs to consumers. The U.S. Department of Agriculture reported Monday the wholesale pork price, known in the industry as the cutout, fell 9 cents to $130.41 per hundred pounds, based on Omaha, Neb., price quotes, after notching consecutive fresh highs last week.

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Kelsey Gee CHICAGO--U.S. hog futures are easing in electronic trade amid profit-taking, following a sharp rally to new all-time highs. Record-breaking pork prices and expectations for supplies of market-ready animals to diminish in the weeks ahead have lifted hog futures 15.5% this month, surging by the daily exchange-imposed limit of three cents per pound for consecutive sessions in the past weeks. Pork processors have had more incentive to aggressively compete for a smaller number of available hogs in the cash markets as retailers have paid record prices for hams, loins, and other pork products.

Headlines.Headline: MARKET TALK: Hormel Sees Peanut Butter Spreading Across China

PARAGRAPH.#text: 10:43 EST - Hormel Foods (HRL), which has been increasing efforts to get Spam onto Chinese store shelves, is betting consumers there will develop a taste for peanut butter as well. Central to its $700M purchase of Skippy from Unilever (UN, ULVR.LN) are expectations of growth in China and synergy with its existing business there. Peanuts and peanut oil are already an important part of the diet in China and other emerging markets, but "those markets are still catching on to American-style peanut butter," HRL CEO Jeffrey Ettinger says. #text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Hormel Foods Corp.'s

fiscal fourth-quarter earnings rose 53% amid lower ingredient, freight and warehouse costs, as growth was led by its refrigerated-food segment. #text:
CHICAGO (CBS.MW) -- Grain pits at the Chicago Board of
    Trade settled mixed Friday in a shortened session for the Thanksgiving holiday weekend.
     Despite a lower close, January soybeansrose early
    amid bullish export sales for the week ended Nov. 20. Early Friday, the U.S.
    Department of Agriculture reported soybean sales at 705,700 metric tons, 25 percent higher
    than last week.
     December corn fell 0.6 percent as export sales were below traders'
    expectations. The USDA reported corn sales at 415,000 metric tons, 65 percent below the
    previous week. Wheat sales were 86 percent higher than last week at 728,900 metric tons.
     January soybeans fell 3 cents to $7.182 per bushel

December
    corn fell 1.6 cents to $2.806 per bushel and December wheat rose 1.6 cents to $3.576
    per bushel on the Chicago Board of Trade.
    
  
  
    
     Livestock markets at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange
    were close to unchanged in quiet trading as many market players extended their holiday.
    The pork complex was basically steady as cash hogs were higher and the product was in
    better shape than it has been for the last several weeks. However, large kills are
    expected next week which prevented a rally. February
    live hogs

fell 0.075 cent to 60.475 cents per pound and February
    pork bellies

fell 0.6 cent to 57.025 cents per pound. 
     Lower cash prices and plentiful supplies weighed on cattle markets.
    Cash cattle trades were primarily 67 cents. Analysts said ifthe market doesn't see
    68 cents trades soon, look for the December contract to show weakness ahead of expiration.
     Feeder cattle was supported by weakness in the corn market. December
    live cattle

fell 0.1 cent to 67.20 cents per pound and March
    feeder cattle

rose 0.05 cent to 79.875 cents per pound.

     An announcement from ministers of the Organization of Petroleum

    futures next week. OPEC has yet to settle on the production ceiling, currently set at 25
